'''Sir Arthur Clive Morrison-Bell, 1st Baronet''' (19 April 1871 &ndash; 16 April 1956), known as '''Arthur Clive Bell''' until 1905, was a [[United Kingdom|British]] soldier and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] parliamentarian.

He was educated at [[Eton College|Eton]] and the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]], and was commissioned in the [[Scots Guards]] in 1890. He served in the [[Second Boer War|Boer War]], was promoted Major in 1908, and retired from the army the same year.

At the [[United Kingdom general election, January 1910|general election of January 1910]], Morrison-Bell was elected [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Honiton (UK Parliament constituency)|Honiton]] and held the seat without a break until 1931, when he retired due to ill-health. In 1914 he rejoined the army at the beginning of the [[First World War]], was captured in 1915 and returned to England in 1918.

In 1912 Morrison-Bell married Lilah Wingfield, considered a great beauty, and they had two daughters, Shelagh and Patricia. In 1923 he was made a [[baronet]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=32849 |date=31 July 1923 |startpage=5238}}</ref> but the title became extinct when he died in 1956.

